The original erroneous code fails because the variable named variable is not assigned a value before the print statement runs. This causes a compilation error since Java requires local variables to be initialized before use.

Here is the corrected version of the original class:

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String variable = "Hello world";
        System.out.println(variable);
    }
}
```

The following class assigns a new value to the same variable name:

```java
public class ValueAssigner {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String variable = "New Value Assigned";
        System.out.println(variable);
    }
}
```

The next class concatenates the variable with another string:

```java
public class StringConcatenator {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String variable = "Hello world";
        String result = variable + " and Java";
        System.out.println(result);
    }
}
```

